Here is an alternate way of finding [perfect numbers](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perfect_number).

- if &lt;B&gt;2&lt;sup&gt;p&lt;/sup&gt;-1&lt;/B&gt; is prime when &lt;B&gt;p&lt;/B&gt; is prime. Then &lt;B&gt;(2&lt;sup&gt;p-1&lt;/sup&gt;)(2&lt;sup&gt;p&lt;/sup&gt;-1)&lt;/B&gt; is a perfect number. &lt;B&gt;2&lt;sup&gt;p&lt;/sup&gt;-1&lt;/B&gt; is known as a [Mersenne Prime](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mersenne_prime#:~:text=In%20mathematics%2C%20a%20Mersenne%20prime,so%20is%202n%20%E2%88%92%201)
- As these numbers get real big real fast, using [BigInteger](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/18/docs/api/java.base/java/math/BigInteger.html) is recommended.

