&gt; and that object cannot contain 2 properties with same name

You&#39;re mistaken. They actually *can*, but then `x` of `C` is said to *hide* `x` of `P`. This is defined in the Java Language Specification (JLS), [&#167; 8.3][1]:

&gt; If a class declares a field with a certain name, then the declaration of that field is said to **hide any and all accessible declarations of fields with the same name in superclasses**, and superinterfaces of the class. 

&lt;sup&gt;(Emphasis mine.)&lt;/sup&gt;

This has two implications:

1. You can refer to `P.x` from within `C` by using `super` (JLS [&#167; 15.11.2][2]):

    ```java
    class C extends P {

        int x;

        void test() {
            System.out.println(super.x);
        }
    }
    ```

2. You cannot refer to `P.x` from another class or a static context (also JLS [&#167; 15.11.2][2]):

    ```java
    class Main {
        public static void main(String[] args) {
            System.out.println(&quot;P.x: &quot; + c.super.x); // Won&#39;t work
        }
    }
    ```

---

Here&#39;s an example showing that `C` can refer to two different `x`s:

```java
class Parent {

    int x;

    Parent() {
        x = 1;
    }
}
```

```java
class Child extends Parent {

    int x;

    Child() {
        x = 2;
    }

    void printBothXs() {
        System.out.println(x);
        System.out.println(super.x);
    }
}
```

```java
public static void main(String[] args) {
    Child c = new Child();
    c.printBothXs();
}
```

